@massich @mrastgoo @chkoar This is to support one-vs-all encoding targets.
This is motivated by the fact that in `keras` a user will one-hot-encode the target to provide it to the loss function. In #409, we will greatly benefit to manage automatically this case by converting the problem to multiclass to make the under-/over-sampling before to convert it back.

It is ready for review or at least some comment regarding the internal changes.

Perhaps we could solve this by treating `char *` as an intrinsic type rather than throwing away the pointer?  I think in practice, `char *` is almost used as a C-style string, not as a pointer to a `char`.  (And, in fact, we don't actually support binding something that is a pointer to a single char--pybind always treats it as a c-style string).

I did try severing this in `make_caster` back in #624, but that was indeed the wrong place.  It might make more sense providing `intrinsic_t` specializations for `char *`, though.

The other solution—and actually, I think this makes logical sense even with the above—is to change the various type casters to make loading `None` an operation require `convert`, so that instead of:
```C++
if (src.is_none()) {
    value = nullptr;
    return true;
}
```
we do:
```C++
if (src.is_none()) {
    if (!convert) return false;
    value = nullptr;
    return true;
}
```

Then the `nullptr_t` caster gets first-pass priority for a None.  That makes a lot of sense anyway; it would mean you could explicitly overload with a `py::none` argument and get the expected behaviour.

